s/news/opinion/3900215.htmInternet can level the political playing field
By Mike McCurry and Larry PurpuroNOT many months from now, people across the =
country will experience one=20
of the great recurring features of American democracy. At shopping=20
malls, on factory floors, at church socials and even on our front=20
stoops, we will be approached by individuals who want to represent us in=20
public office. While chances are high that we won't know them=20
personally, they will walk up to us, offer a handshake and a flier and=20
ask for our votes.Just as technology is affecting every other area of communi=
cation, it=20
has begun to affect the way political candidates communicate with voters.In t=
his year's GOP gubernatorial primary, California Secretary of State=20
Bill Jones, who faced better-funded candidates, acquired the e-mail=20
addresses of more than a million potential California voters and sent=20
each an unsolicited e-mail asking for support.That day, he might have chosen =
any of the more traditional -- and more=20
expensive -- methods of contacting voters, such as direct mail, radio=20
spots or TV ads. But he spent only about 2 cents per message, instead of=20
35 cents or more per message for direct mail or in another medium.Had Jones c=
hosen direct mail, radio or TV, that communication would have=20
been equally ``unsolicited,'' as defined in the e-mail world. Few voters=20
would have ``opted in'' to receive campaign information from Jones=20
through any of those channels.The response to Jones' e-mail effort, however, =
was swift and intense. He=20
was lambasted by anti-spam advocates, and media coverage was almost=20
entirely negative. To be fair, some of Jones' tactics could have been=20
refined. He used a less-than-perfect list and no standard-practice=20
``paid for'' disclaimer in the message.His detractors, however, attacked him =
not for his tactical miscues but=20
because the e-mail was sent unsolicited. In fact, Jones' online campaign=20
may have been his most visible asset. In an era of cynicism toward money=20
in politics -- money typically spent on other unsolicited communication=20
mediums -- Jones tried to level the playing field.No one likes commercial spa=
m. It is irrelevant and untargeted and can be=20
highly intrusive and even offensive. But as a sophisticated society,=20
it's time to differentiate commercial spam from very different=20
unsolicited e-mail sent by political candidates to voters.The debate is parti=
cularly relevant in light of legislation in Congress=20
that would constitute the first federal law to directly address spam. We=20
believe e-mail is no more intrusive than direct mail, telemarketing or=20
TV advertising when it comes to politicians seeking to reach voters. A=20
simple link in good e-mail campaigns allows recipients to opt out of=20
future mailings. Direct mail takes at least a phone call or stamp to be=20
taken off a list, and viewers must repeatedly endure TV ads.When a candidate =
lacks a large campaign war chest, he or she can use the=20
Internet to provide constituents with information to better prepare them=20
to perform their civic duty of casting educated votes. With more than 60=20
percent of all potential voters in this country possessing e-mail=20
accounts, it makes sense that political candidates use this medium.Candidates=
 might avoid some of the tactical problems encountered by the=20
Jones campaign if they use the technologies available today that better=20
ensure quality of e-mail lists and target content to specific recipient=20
groups.But the broader point remains. When a political candidate sends a vote=
r=20
an e-mail, that recipient can choose to delete the message without=20
opening it, unsubscribe from the list, read it or even reply and engage=20
the sender. That choice should belong to the voter -- not to anti-spam=20
advocates whose efforts are better focused on commercial e-mail.=20
Political candidates should be free to communicate with voters as best=20
they can, and let voters decide what to do with that information.
